<h1>LG Washer Repair Cost in Los Angeles</h1>

<p>LG washer repair in Los Angeles runs anywhere from $150 for a simple drain clog to $480 for a motor, with most common repairs landing in the $280–400 range. Here's an honest breakdown of what the typical fixes cost, what drives the price up or down, and when a repair beats replacing the machine. The $65 diagnostic is waived when you approve the work. Call (323) 990-7550.</p>

<h2>What LG Washer Repairs Typically Cost</h2>
<p>Here's where the common LG washer jobs land, parts and labor included. A drain pump replacement runs $280–360, a door boot seal $250–320, a drum bearing $320–420, a motor $380–480, a water inlet valve $280–340, and a control board up to $420. Plenty of problems cost far less than that, though — a clogged pump filter behind a <a href="/washer/symptoms/lg-washer-not-draining/">washer that won't drain</a>, or an off-balance load that stops the spin, is often just the service call with nothing to replace. The same goes for many error codes: an <a href="/washer/error-codes/lg-washer-oe-error/">OE drain fault</a> is frequently a blockage we clear on the spot rather than a failed part, so the symptom or code your machine is showing has a lot to do with the final number.</p>

<h2>What Affects the Price</h2>
<p>Two things move an LG washer repair cost: the part itself and how much labor it takes to reach it. A pump or inlet valve is a modest part; a control board or motor is not. Labor swings even wider — clearing a filter takes minutes, while a drum bearing means pulling the drum and splitting the tub, a two-to-three-hour job. Front-load machines generally cost a little more to work on than top-loaders because of the way they come apart, and harder-to-source parts on older models can add to the total. Whatever the job, our techs diagnose on-site and quote a fixed number before any work starts.</p>

<h2>Repair vs a New LG Washer</h2>
<p>A comparable new LG washer runs $800–1,500 by the time it's delivered and installed, so most single-part repairs are a fraction of replacing the machine. A pump, seal, valve, or even a bearing on an otherwise healthy washer is an easy call. Replacement only really makes sense when an older machine has several major parts failing at once — and in that case we'll tell you straight rather than sell you a repair that won't hold.</p>

<h2>What's Included and Our Diagnostic</h2>
<p>Every repair uses OEM parts and carries a one-year warranty on parts and labor. The $65 diagnostic is waived when you approve the repair, so on almost every job you pay the repair price, not the repair price plus a fee. There are no hidden charges and no surcharge for same-day or weekend work — the number we quote on-site is the number you pay.</p>

